commit_message:
Skip test_deploy_app_with_volume_creation_from_backup test to unblock murano gate

Since Idd6c6be1c8bdf4dcf730f67e75a58a0329fe5259 this commit add the
jsonschema validation for backup restore, restore a volume using null
name or uuid will failed. This breaks the original process.
So we skip this test, when it fixed, revert this patch.

Change-Id: Iaba14c48e1a4f7d837df4a9881953d2cfa311545

commit_message:
Add ability to manage non-inventory hosts

We may want to load balance to existing services that we aren't managing
via ansible. Currently the hosts have to exist in the inventory in order
to add a VIP for these hosts, this patch adds the ability to set the
hostnames and addresses of the hosts manually when they aren't in the
ansible inventory.

Additionally, this patch adds a test for both the group method and the
host_lists method.

Change-Id: Ida66f401d8320d9bf14eac9b8014124631978808

commit_message:
Allow check experimental jobs to gather logs

The experimental jobs would not have scripts/test-log-collect.sh
in src/zuul.project.canonical_name, so we need to point to the
appropriate folder. This is already done for the run job, so
we are re-using the same mechanics.

Change-Id: I26cc8c808fb34c426d5599e0023f9285c66cf1ed

commit_message:
Modified default pubsub mechanism to etcd

In setups where we have etcd installed, we now use etcd pubsub instead
of the zmq pubsub.
This is more natural and prevents issues during the install process.

Change-Id: I23fa9b1282eea53c3a05af6324644c1c815a491d

Add all-in-one vagrant config

Add the ability to launch an all-in-one dragonflow vm via vagrant
The syntax of the launch is:
vagrant up devstack_aio

Refactor vagrant configuration

Unified the compute nodes in the vagrant file
Renamed the configuration file to dragonflow.conf.yml (from
virtualbox.conf.yml) as it is now not hypervisor-specific

commit_message:
use hashmap to quickly find matching resource def

we shouldn't waste our time looping through resources and searching
metrics to find a match. just build hashmap and find the resource
based on metric.

this removes fnmatch functionality because we don't match on
wildcards and the code itself actually requires metric names to be
explicit to create_metrics

Change-Id: I2398247270217759c876ab5a9b60038dad79a9d3

  concurrently. Let's use regular instance methods instead.

* Cherry-picked tempest change from mistral project:

commit_message:
Remove all class methods in tempest tests

* Using class methods for setup can create issues when tests are run
  concurrently. Let's use regular instance methods instead.

* Cherry-picked tempest change from mistral project:
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/527348/

Change-Id: I43a8c3bf2d565892fbd45a1efe0abbb0cf7c11d5

commit_message:
Add root-show to OSC

This change adds database support for the python-openstackclient
project for the root-show command.

The trove command root-show is now:
    openstack database root show

Change-Id: I621f41d0c920306fed5502f30e1de3806b911929
Partially-Implements: blueprint trove-support-in-python-openstackclient
Signed-off-by: Zhao Chao <zhaochao1984@gmail.com>

commit_message:
k8s_atomic: Remove kubelet and kube-proxy from master

Currently we start kubelet as unscheduled. Before
containerizing kube. we needed to run kubelet before as
unscheduled to run the controller-manager, scheduler and
kube-proxy as static pods. There is no such need anymore.

Change-Id: I0e36606427530756d8084b643ba43880541bbe44
Partially-Implements: blueprint run-kube-as-container
Closes-Bug: #1726482

commit_message:
Clarify adding -e argument for image prepare command

This is now a bit confusing, as running the command in the docs creates
a yaml file with zero services in it.  So instead show how to reference
the default docker.yaml environment, and mention users can pass their
own environment files here.

Change-Id: I8e17b16e4386c9e800ef37639554668448689983

k8s_atomic: Add server to kubeconfig

Since 1.6 --apiservers is deprecated and it is removed in
1.8. Add the server parameter in kubeconfig and remove
--apiservers.

Closes-Bug: #1718926

[{'created': '2018-01-10 18:37:58.000000000', 'message': 'WIP Render bond-with-vlans for all roles

This switches the bond-with-vlans config and environments to
render for all roles, including custom roles.

Note the "special" -v6 and -no-external templates are still only
rendered for the controller since they aren't used for any
other roles, and we should really enable networks/ipv6 via
the roles_data/network_data interfaces now.

In an effort to avoid operator impact, the old inconsistent
config filenames are still rendered, but we should look
at ways to move away from these to the consistent rolename-role.yaml.

Change-Id: Id7c6f999d62b1946564398f69d59e254158425b7

commit_message:
WIP Render bond-with-vlans for all roles

This switches the bond-with-vlans config and environments to
render for all roles, including custom roles.

Note the "special" -v6 and -no-external templates are still only
rendered for the controller since they aren't used for any
other roles, and we should really enable networks/ipv6 via
the roles_data/network_data interfaces now.

In an effort to avoid operator impact, the old inconsistent
config filenames are still rendered, but we should look
at ways to move away from these to the consistent rolename-role.yaml.

Change-Id: Id7c6f999d62b1946564398f69d59e254158425b7

commit_message:
Modify the docker install step of quickstart doc

The original way 'curl -sSL https://get.docker.io | bash' has some
problem. It will make the operating system version does not match the
docker version. I am executing this command on centos 7.2. The installed docker
version is 'docker-ce-17.12.0.ce-1.el7.centos.x86_64'. However, this
version requires centos 7.4.

Change-Id: I055615a272733c7b267d42451a1835b5b5efbae1

commit_message:
Follow Zuul v3 naming conventions

Follow the conventions for naming jobs in Zuul v3: Rename jobs.

For details, see
https://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/drivers.html#consistent-naming-for-jobs-with-zuul-v3

Leave some old names, since murano-tempest-plugin needs them. A followup
will remove them.

Needed-By: I547d972bb6b82bc93addf19bd3f989e431950ab2
Change-Id: Id3784a6339b444531d118ab39b19f5a316d87872

commit_message:
Add validate_instances_network for cluster create.

Before create instance node for a cluster, it should validate
the flavor, the volume, the quotas and the networks. But only
galera_common valdiate the network, the other datastores miss.

Change-Id: I1233b47b57e2775d19627c1c7807988ddbe16130

commit_message:
Fix issue the deleted item is selected again with batch delete

Items recently deleted with batch action are shown in deletion
confirmation dialog when execute the batch delete action again.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Create 2 new items
2. Delete one of them using the batch delete action on top of the table
3. Select the another item and click the batch delete action

Expect to see the confirmation dialog shows one selected item,
but it shows the item that was deleted in step 2 as well.
Also, HTTP DELETE method for already deleted item is submitted
again and occurs error.

This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: Ib475761363e85be8df3c64e94d8000295796fd1c
Closes-Bug: #1742599

commit_message:
Fix issue the deleted item is selected again with batch delete

Items recently deleted with batch action are shown in deletion
confirmation dialog when execute the batch delete action again.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Create 2 new items
2. Delete one of them using the batch delete action on top of the table
3. Select the another item and click the batch delete action

Expect to see the confirmation dialog shows one selected item,
but it shows the item that was deleted in step 2 as well.
Also, HTTP DELETE method for already deleted item is submitted
again and occurs error.

This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: I6555f3d2a4c0f9a4fb9f3fa780f31e3d2b03f34e
Closes-Bug: #1742599

commit_message:
Save env variables for logs collection and reproducing

We use some generated environment variables in logs collection role
but since it runs in multinode jobs in post playbook, we don't have
them avaiable. Preserver them in collect_log.sh file.

Closes-Bug: #1743140
Change-Id: I0614d2e4e576b818bffb093327f0f8857d122810

Update doc on proxy

This patchset adds in additional note to allow users to
use the OpenStack client to connect to the services without
the connection routed to the proxy, if one exists.

commit_message:
Add root-enable to OSC

This change adds database support for the python-openstackclient
project for the root-enable command.

The trove command root-enable is now:
    openstack database root enable

Change-Id: I121dbe09bc10c57358c091e1eb882c816df6d4b2
Partially-Implements: blueprint trove-support-in-python-openstackclient
Signed-off-by: Zhao Chao <zhaochao1984@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Remove logical_nvdimm_n from ilo inspection

Remove the logical_nvdimm_n from ilo
inspection as the hardware release with this
feature is postponed.

Closes-bug: 1721175

Depends-On: I5ed3208a36845c699620a0e9c88e769a3e1e60b4
Change-Id: I756f369d8514d34dbfeedaf0b29ea0a602fb9fba

Yes that's what I had in mind.

But to correct the serialization problem it may be the case that we need to perform this conversion on the agent to get a canonical form of the option description (more precisely in default function of OptionJsonEncoder in generator.py)

As it is hard to check this change with the agent disabled and reenabling the agent requires changing the serialization. I have mixed feelings about it."}, {'account_id': 23518, 'date': '2018-01-12 15:48:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Check if certificates must be verified in the vim

This patch tries to fix the bug: https://bugs.launchpad.net/tacker/+bug/1719841

To disable the verification, a parameter must be included in vim_config.yaml
file.
cert_verify: 'False'

Co-Authored-By: Cong Phuoc Hoang <hoangphuocbk2.07@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1719841

Change-Id: If9c8eab81bad2028ae146598d559831bc51cbbf5
Signed-off-by: Manuel Buil <mbuil@suse.com>

commit_message:
Remove python-dev from list of preinstalled packages

python-dev package causes cloud-init to fail on Fedora-based
distros because the package is called python-devel there.
Since this package is present in python-pip recommended dependencies
and thus going to be installed anyway, there is no need to include
it explicitly. With this fix it becomes possible to use bare
Fedora cloud image with murano.

Change-Id: I276839b9ba772d8f0a6bac975b204b0308839170

commit_message:
Add "cert_verify" in vim_config file to support insecure VIM

Currently, Tacker can not communicate with VIM endpoints that
use SSL. This patch will add cert_verify parameter, user can
set "cert_verify" to False (default value is True) to disable
verifying SSL.

Change-Id: I0af2a0f91ecda2a63cf6233d780e1dd7c064513c

Tom,if use generic driver and cinder volume attach the Svm as the share, how to ensure data synchronization in both Svms？Should we attach the cinder volume to both Svms?'}, {'account_id': 9003, 'date': '2017-12-19 03:14:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

> Tom,if use generic driver and cinder volume attach the Svm as the share, how to ensure data synchronization in both Svms？Should we attach the cinder volume to both Svms?

@haobing: You make a very good observation.  I have been thinking about this issue in the context of the ceph-nfs back end primarily, though it would be nice to have a solution that works for the generic driver as well.  (We want to get HA for the ganesha gateway for the ceph-nfs back end via SVMs or containers so that we can scale these out on compute nodes, but initially we deploy these on controller nodes so that we can get HA via the controller-node pacemaker cluster.)  In any case, the ceph-nfs driver has a networked connection to the back end CephFS storage so it is not subject to the problem that you raise.

For generic driver a solution that resurrects the share server on a new node may be superior so that the "same" nova instance exists after the initial node has died. That way one doesn't have to worry about data synchronization.  Alternatively, one might develop a "takeover" hook wherein the surviving member of the HA pair fences off the old SVM and then attaches the backing cinder volume (it wouldn't have had it attached before).  This could be quite complicated.

I by no means intend any of the above to be the last word on HA for the generic driver.  I know a number of folks are interested in getting it to be production-worthy so maybe some of them have a better idea.'}, {'account_id': 19554, 'date': '2017-12-19 03:46:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)

I just want to notify that there are two typos in my option. Please update it until this patch is merged.'}, {'account_id': 27577, 'date': '2018-01-15 01:38:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}]

commit_message:
RFC: remove `keystone` from endpoint lookup function names

This PS removes `keystone` from endpoint lookup function names.
They are not keystone specific, and only reference keystone as this
was their original use case.

Change-Id: Icef11d258a1969635a52368d28d562d51e470ca6

commit_message:
quota: Use neutron default quota (read-only) API

Neutron provides an API to retrieve default quotas since newton.
Unfortunately there is no corresponding neutron API extension
is not defined, so there is no way to detect it via API.
The API exists since newton, so this commit just switches to
the default quota API.

Closes-Bug: #1337473
blueprint make-quotas-great-again
Change-Id: Ia826b67f4cec7d95335c62ef98c3040feaa06117

Fix typos in all-in-one code example and add auth info

This PS simply fixes a few typos in an all-in-one code block
example dedicated to setting up the gateway. It also adds
additional information about how to set up auth information
to use the python-openstackclient.

commit_message:
Fix reserve volume enforcing the wrong policy action

This PS fixes `reserve_volume` enforcing the wrong
policy action: retype policy. It has been corrected
to reserve volume policy. This is consistent with
the policy in code documentation as well for both
policies: retype is only enforced by os-retype and
reserve is only enforced by os-reserve [0][1]

[0] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/94460b64fb06814e18a4459e365cf207b730210b/cinder/policies/volume_actions.py#L91
[1] https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/94460b64fb06814e18a4459e365cf207b730210b/cinder/policies/volume_actions.py#L197

Change-Id: I14b8288cdb066f30b66068dcaaf66e1277aa122f

(in tempest repo) that is part of our queues.

commit_message:
Fix version details API does not return 200 OK

When use version details api http://ip:8786/v2 to get api details,
it does not return 200 OK, and the return value is empty.

This change is to correct the version details API URL and its
sample response.

Change-Id: I547dca649db22b31051b490c2b230322d3c9d479

I have one more concern about it (probably because I don't know logging API well). I docs in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/480117/18/doc/source/admin/config-logging.rst I read that it works only with openvswitch firewall driver currently. Shouldn't it be somehow forced in devstack plugin also then?"}, {'account_id': 15471, 'date': '2017-12-20 09:50:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 36:

Hi Slawek,

Thanks for your great reviewing.

> I have one more concern about it (probably because I don't know logging API well). I docs in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/480117/18/doc/source/admin/config-logging.rst I read that it works only with openvswitch firewall driver currently. Shouldn't it be somehow forced in devstack plugin also then?

If there is no compatible log_driver, then API will prevent a requesting successful from creating log_object[1][2]. So I think we don't need to add some constraint here. Do you think so?

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/services/logapi/logging_plugin.py#L73
[2]https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/services/logapi/common/validators.py#L133"}, {'account_id': 11975, 'date': '2017-12-23 15:10:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 36: Code-Review+2

> Hi Slawek,
 > 
 > Thanks for your great reviewing.
 > 
 > > I have one more concern about it (probably because I don't know
 > logging API well). I docs in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/480117/18/doc/source/admin/config-logging.rst
 > I read that it works only with openvswitch firewall driver
 > currently. Shouldn't it be somehow forced in devstack plugin also
 > then?
 > 
 > If there is no compatible log_driver, then API will prevent a
 > requesting successful from creating log_object[1][2]. So I think we
 > don't need to add some constraint here. Do you think so?
 > 
 > [1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/services/logapi/logging_plugin.py#L73
 > [2]https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/neutron/services/logapi/common/validators.py#L133

Ok, I was thinking about it for a while and I think that it shouldn't be forced to use specific firewall driver when logging api will be enabled. It might be confusing for users and we might forget about it when support for some other driver will also be in the future.
But I think that this limitation should be strictly written in documentation :)"}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2017-12-24 12:03:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 36: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

IMHO there is no need for a guard on combination of firewall driver and log driver in DevStack. Documentation and good error log would help us. If we have more confusion in future, let's improve it."}, {'account_id': 15471, 'date': '2018-01-11 02:59:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 36:

Some 'test_extract_key' tests are in unit, maybe you need to rename these."}, {'account_id': 21414, 'date': '2018-01-11 07:45:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> Some 'test_extract_key' tests are in unit, maybe you need to rename
 > these.

I'm not sure this is relevant to this change.

The `extract_key` **feature** is still available, it just no longer uses the dedicated **method**. The test case name `test_extract_key` fits its content, in my opinion."}, {'account_id': 19159, 'date': '2018-01-11 08:11:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

> The `extract_key` **feature** is still available, it just no longer

 > fits its content, in my opinion.

I'm not if extract_key can be named "a feature" :-) 
As I see it, test_extract_key used to test the _extract_key method, and now it tests the _create_entity_key method. So I agree with dwj that it's a good idea to rename it (although the current name is also valid). commit_message:
Add index(updated_at) on migrations table.

A database index will be added on migrations.updated_at to
improve the performance of filtering migrations by
‘changes-since’ parameter.

Change-Id: I6bf9e498597669c8641f78267d7da589d01ad786
Implement: blueprint add-pagination-and-change-since-for-migration-list

commit_message:
Gate: 5 Node basic gate

This PS adds a 5 node basic gate for OSH, using the same format as the
dev-deploy guide. Follow on commits will:
 * Remove redundant gate scripts
 * Add documentation, in the same format as the AIO guide
 * Add all remaining services in OSH
 * Enable Helm test for all services

Change-Id: I7b72dc4777e88cae2b8a4d842c41a17a526079a2
Depends-On: Ie9b23174fade3df4a87f2b771ea654e2081b4f4e

commit_message:
Align stars to fix stable/pike gate on scenario001

1) Fix path for iscsi config file

We changed the bind mount to be /etc/iscsi in
I838427ccae06cfe1be72939c4bcc2978f7dc36a8, we need to copy the files to
/etc/iscsi so that they do not end up at '/' in the container.

Change-Id: Id5c1f16d08ffd36a35a6669d64460a7b2240d401
Closes-Bug: #1741850
(cherry picked from commit 8eb351d588539c20caf768c2633832a924f40690)

2) Fix puppet config volume for iscsid in containers

Bind mount the /etc/iscsi host path for iscsi container puppet config.
Use the real host path /etc/iscsi for containers dependsing on it.

Closes-bug: #1735425

Change-Id: I838427ccae06cfe1be72939c4bcc2978f7dc36a8
Co-authored-by: Alan Bishop <abishop@redhat.com>
Co-authored-by: Martin André <m.andre@redhat.com>
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobreli@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 82f128f15b1b1eb7bf6ac7df0c6d01e5619309eb)

3) Allow to override manage polling param

Without this, we cannot override the polling yaml metrics
from puppet template.

Change-Id: I509dd4932402c458e222c52b5d7d5e370a5466c0
(cherry picked from commit e870783b2c8f3b7b13459693b17425f5bf0fe53d)

commit_message:
Update Ceph container CPU/memory limits in Ceph scenarios

Ceph containers are started with `docker run --memory`
and `docker run --cpus` to limit their memory and CPU
resources. The defaults for OSD and MDS containers were
recently increased [1] to values better for production
but this change keeps them at lower values just for
CI.

[1] https://github.com/ceph/ceph-ansible/pull/2304

Change-Id: I5b5cf5cc52907af092bea5e162d4b577ee05c23a
Related-Bug: 1741499

commit_message:
Gate: Simplify and speed up pod and k8s object log collection

This PS simplifys and accelerates the collection of pod container
logs and k8s object info in the zuul gates, which can currently take
40 minutes for the 5 node OSH gate to complete.

Change-Id: Ie9b23174fade3df4a87f2b771ea654e2081b4f4e

commit_message:
Support webhook

- Allow user create webhook based on the function.
- Webhook can be invoked without authentication.
- Can not delete function associated with webhook.

Another big change is, we are going to use minikube instead of
kubernetes-aio scripts from openstack-helm project.

Implements: blueprint qinling-function-webhook
Change-Id: I85e0b0f999f0d820bfacca9ac3b9af04e80df0d7

When mongodb create a database, if there is no content in the
database, it will not create database. At the same time, trove

commit_message:
Fix mongodb database create

When mongodb create a database, if there is no content in the
database, it will not create database. At the same time, trove
database-list will not displayed. The solution is to create an
empty collection as content.

Closes-Bug: #1720124
Change-Id: I0d74553003648c923da538a6db4fe0a050343179

commit_message:
Update repo_server role for apt-cacher-ng fix

On Ubuntu Xenial Apt-Cacher NG fails to start
because log directories are not created.  This
brings that fix into newton.

Change-Id: I981895f8e59b02f3f5ab2bd73188429b130dccda

commit_message:
Allow to override manage polling param

Without this, we cannot override the polling yaml metrics
from puppet template.

Change-Id: I509dd4932402c458e222c52b5d7d5e370a5466c0

messages:
[{'account_id': 27616, 'date': '2018-01-11 05:28:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2018-01-11 05:28:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and

Migrate to override_role for network multiprovider tests

Now that override_role has supplanted switch_role (which has
been deprecated) in [0], the RBAC tests need to switch to use
override_role.

test_networks_multiprovider_rbac.

commit_message:
Remove deprecated services binary CLI arg

The services CLI 'binary' arg was deprecated in Pike
via change Idd0d2be960ca0ed59097c10c931da47a1a3e66fb
because with cells v2 support in the API, the binary
argument for the enable/disable CLIs doesn't make sense
as the only binary those work with is 'nova-compute'.
So this removes the deprecated argument and hard-codes
the value to be 'nova-compute'.

Change-Id: I60490f3d74212bb172dccc1c7d337198e1021236

commit_message:
Remove deprecated fixedip/floatingip/virtual interface CLIs/APIs

The add-fixed-ip, remove-fixed-ip, floating-ip-associate,
floating-ip-disassociate, and virtual-interface-list CLIs
and related python API bindings were deprecated in the 9.0.0
release in Pike via change Ie76283962c375b735f30ccb3053db07cf2330de2.
This removes the CLIs and related python API bindings and will go
into the 10.0.0 release.

Change-Id: Icb667973c65d26395db660b1c7b919550db66d08

commit_message:
Relocate utils tests to match the main code

commit 75700a7b4247773cf1f919b40e70ba89ba92bddb introduced
utils/ directory in the main code, but the test code was not relocated.
Locations of test codes should match corresponding main codes.
This commit relocates utils test codes.

Note that osc_lib.tests.utils is a module exposed to osc-lib consumers,
so it is moved to osc_lib/tests/utils/__init__.py not to break
existing imports.

Change-Id: Ib134ba6568396dcb9c6502c3f8f292823fdc1564

commit_message:
Use stestr for coverage

Change [1] restored .testr.conf since it was needed for the
manila coverage job.

Modify script used by the coverage job to invoke stestr rather
than setup.py with testr so that this job no longer requires
.testr.conf so remove the dotfile and update .gitignore.

TrivialFix

[1] I451e383ed654d00a5a017cb28521c47566911f33

Change-Id: Id1e533b52dc8e141cf834c2e5ed2ed91b73e198c

commit_message:
Deprecate the allow-multiattach option to create

This patch just marks the option as deprecated, going
forward we'll go with using a volume-type instead.

Change-Id: I00615495a6ed98a996135192ed41719b2b00d936
blueprint: multi-attach-v3-attach

A couple of issues here - the major one:

I have no clue why you need this element: this kind of package is highly dependent on the used virtualization layer. Also the VM can (once) boot without this package installed. Therefore IMHO this should go into the configuration management step (and should not be done during the 'golden image' build).

Some minor things:

* Please fill in a sensible commit message
* Please provide a Readme that explains / references an explanation why and how a user should need this element.
* Please use package-install / pkg-map for installing elements (currently you only support a sub-set of the distributions)
* There is an environment variable out which gives information about the used init system: please use this."}, {'account_id': 5263, 'date': '2017-12-18 04:01:58.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer Jenkins with the following votes:

* Verified-1 by Jenkins (3)
'}, {'account_id': 7488, 'date': '2018-01-13 15:39:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
DO_NOT_MERGE: Use better URL for China

Usage: This patch is using kolla dockerfile customization feature.
During run build script. add following parameter

./tools/build.py --template-override etc/kolla/kolla-template-override.j2 ...

* download heka and rabbitmq package from cdn
* download get-pip.py from cnd
* use China Ubuntu source mirror
* use pypi mirror from ustcustc.edu.cn

WARNING: this PS should never be merged

Change-Id: I7fab296c9217a5669fa7396bda013523a30b6e7a
Signed-off-by: Jeffrey Zhang <zhang.lei.fly@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Avoid Forcing the Translation of Translatable Variables

Whenever possible translation should not be forced by use of
six.text_type() on a message being used with a format string.

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html#avoid-forcing-the-translation-of-translatable-variables

Change-Id: I2a4d84ea556bc637cf5646e7beee5d5228fd3157

commit_message:
Remove logs reserved time from deploy_timeout args

After https://review.openstack.org/#/c/531884/ was merged, we
don't need anymore to save 10 minutes for logs collection
in multinode jobs. Still need this in ovb jobs though.

Change-Id: I9942b5e088f0d46608e7b2bd6569ff39a0736306

[{'created': '2017-10-04 14:17:44.000000000', 'message': 'CLI tests: switch to --os-project-name

All the clients which are wrapped by some method of the CLIClient class
and which use cmd_with_auth support the --os-project-name at least until
Liberty.
Only exception: the keystone client, which was removed in Newton, so
it is not supported anyway (and it has not been fixed).

commit_message:
CLI tests: Identity v3 (project name, api version)

Switch to --os-project-name instead of --os-tenant-name, and pass
also --os-identity-api-version.
All the clients which are wrapped by some method of the CLIClient class
and which use cmd_with_auth support the newly introduced flags at least
since Liberty.
Only exception: the keystone client, which was removed in Newton, so
it is not supported anyway (and it has not been fixed).

Closes-Bug: #1721553
Change-Id: I6d34e76b4089be024093a75f9e467d273d80f1c2

commit_message:
Fix mocking of ovsdb connection in UT

After support for ovsdbapp 0.4.0 was added in
Id22faa1f6179c2fdf8a136972d65f10749c9fc2e
different connection object should be patched to mock
connection to ovsdb in unit tests.
This patch fixes issue with wrong patched module in tests for
logapi agent extension.

Change-Id: I98ee3be7854f6a89edfedd2a4fa38af0ce7d81e4
Closes-Bug: #1742797

(1 comment)

I tested this change on Fedora 27 on top of my change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/531819/ but ./stack.sh failed.

"systemctl  status httpd.service" complains with: "httpd[2317]: AH00534: httpd: Configuration error: More than one MPM loaded."

My /etc/httpd/conf.modules.d/00-mpm.conf file contains:

LoadModule mpm_worker_module modules/mod_mpm_worker.so
LoadModule mpm_event_module modules/mod_mpm_event.so

But I ran stack.sh without this change and it failed, and then I ran stack.sh again with the change. I don't know if it explains my issue.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2018-01-08 16:38:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

My error occurred when calling "install_apache_uwsgi" at stack.sh:809. This function doesn't seem to run the sed fixes of the install_apache_wsgi function which is modified by the change.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2018-01-08 16:40:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Running manually the 3 sed commands of install_apache_wsgi worked around my bug:

sudo sed -i '/mod_mpm_prefork.so/s/^/#/g' /etc/httpd/conf.modules.d/00-mpm.conf
sudo sed -i '/mod_mpm_event.so/s/^/#/g' /etc/httpd/conf.modules.d/00-mpm.conf
sudo sed -i '/mod_mpm_worker.so/s/^#//g' /etc/httpd/conf.modules.d/00-mpm.conf"}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2018-01-11 15:18:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Looks like devstack assumes you are sting with a working apache config. Even tough the old version of devstack made your config wrong  solving that issue is out of scope for this change.

Do you have any issue with a clean install with the new version (after this change) ?

'Closes-Bug: #1740194' can be used by this change, I started this change far sooner than the LP ticket created. 

I can add this to the commit message, but I am not sure just for that we really want to re-spin.."}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2018-01-11 15:20:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2018-01-12 01:08:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Add Fedora 27 support

Removing the (f23,)f24 support they are EOL.
The only non-trivial change is the apache-httpd default worker change,
however might not be bad idea to use `event` instead of `worker`
in the future, but for now keep it AS-IS and continue to use `worker`.

Change-Id: I96d414a30b58bc4b43da45066fdf310a6a830079
Closes-Bug: #1740194

commit_message:
[Sensu] Don't use gem based plugins

Kolla developers added gem based Sensu plugins installation for queens+.
This patch adds override as the above change is making sensu-client image
build fail in TripleO environment.

Closes-Bug: #1742731
Change-Id: I5d1f0992cc3f16fb156ae2324559a529c0ef3a44

commit_message:
Use _update_x_timestamp method in object controller DELETE method

The DELETE method repeats inline the same behaviour as provided by
_update_x_timestamp, so just call the method.

Also add unit tests for the behaviour of _update_x_timestamp.

Change-Id: I8b6cfdbfb54b6d43ac507f23d84309ab543374aa

subject: Remove un-needed hack in probetest
messages:
[{'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-11 22:34:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2018-01-12 08:53:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I remember this workaround. Before the related change we could end up with some nodes having expired data files at t1 and other node(s) having a tombstone at t1. Running the replicators cleaned up the transient inconsistency.

Now we should always ssync an expired object and get another expired object on the receiver. So the replication cycle should not be necessary.

I ran the patched probe test several times to confirm all is ok.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-12 15:11:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-13 01:16:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck'}]

[{'created': '2018-01-11 22:34:30.000000000', 'message': "Remove un-needed hack in probetest

If you ran this probe test with ssync before the related change it would
demonstrate the related bug.  The hack isn't harmful, but it isn't
needed anymore.

Related-Change-Id: I7f90b732c3268cb852b64f17555c631d668044a8
Related-Bug: 1652323

Change-Id: I09e3984a0500a0f4eceec392e7970b84070a5b39
"}]
commit_message:
Remove un-needed hack in probetest

If you ran this probe test with ssync before the related change it would
demonstrate the related bug.  The hack isn't harmful, but it isn't
needed anymore.

Related-Change-Id: I7f90b732c3268cb852b64f17555c631d668044a8
Related-Bug: 1652323

Change-Id: I09e3984a0500a0f4eceec392e7970b84070a5b39

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-20 23:58:55.000000000', 'message': 'Track provider traits in report client

With this change, SchedulerReportClient keeps track of resource provider
traits in the same way as aggregates.  Specifically:

- We use ProviderTree methods to save trait information for each
  provider.
- We refresh trait information along with aggregate information whenever
  we "ensure" a provider exists.

Note that this change set consolidates the refreshing (including cache
expiry) of aggregate and trait associations into a single method.  The
theory being that both aggregate associations and trait associations
should change out of band with roughly the same frequency (i.e. very
rarely).

Change-Id: I33d01d8cab43ce6cdde151d2e9429921a140e88d

commit_message:
Track provider traits in report client

With this change, SchedulerReportClient keeps track of resource provider
traits in the same way as aggregates.  Specifically:

- We use ProviderTree methods to save trait information for each
  provider.
- We refresh trait information along with aggregate information whenever
  we "ensure" a provider exists.

Note that this change set consolidates the refreshing (including cache
expiry) of aggregate and trait associations into a single method.  The
theory being that both aggregate associations and trait associations
should change out of band with roughly the same frequency (i.e. very
rarely).

Change-Id: I33d01d8cab43ce6cdde151d2e9429921a140e88d

commit_message:
Convert tags to when statements for Q major upgrade workflow

This converts "tags: stepN" to "when: step|int == N" for the direct
execution as an ansible playbook, with a loop variable 'step'.
The tasks all include the explicit cast |int.

This also adds a set_fact task for handling of the package removal
with the UpgradeRemovePackages parameter (no change to the interface)

The yaml-validate also now checks for duplicate 'when:' statements

Q upgrade spec @ Ibde21e6efae3a7d311bee526d63c5692c4e27b28

commit_message:
Install additional packages using kolla mechanism

The RUN instruction that installed yum packages was missing the "yum
cleanup" to remove yum cache, causing image size to grow. Use kolla's
packages_append mechanism instead to saves us the trouble of cleaning
up after ourselves, and also ensuring the package installs are
happening in one single yum install call. This results in quicker
builds since we don't have to re-sync repos each time.

Change-Id: I3b9bff1eaf6ac4c59aa28e636dc96da71151bff1
Closes-Bug: #1739025

commit_message:
update example repos to more closely match OSP 13 requirements

comment only change.
rh-common is no longer used for RHEL 7.4 or later
OSP 13/queens will use ceph 3

These may not be final repos for OSP 13.  please check Red Hat
documentation for the official list.

commit_message:
Fix issue the deleted item is selected again with batch delete

Items recently deleted with batch action are shown in deletion
confirmation dialog when execute the batch delete action again.

Steps to reproduce:
1. Create 2 new items
2. Delete one of them using the batch delete action on top of the table
3. Select the another item and click the batch delete action

Expect to see the confirmation dialog shows one selected item,
but it shows the item that was deleted in step 2 as well.
Also, HTTP DELETE method for already deleted item is submitted
again and occurs error.

This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: I5940b3b073d5bb9273068c22e090e3af390c9792
Closes-Bug: #1742599

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-11-10 21:27:03.000000000', 'message': "Test helper: validate provider summaries

Introduce a helper method in AllocationCandidatesTestCase called
_validate_provider_summaries.  In a similar vein to
_validate_allocation_requests, it allows the consumer to specify the
expected value in a terse and readable format, e.g.:

        expected = {
            'cn1': [
                (fields.ResourceClass.VCPU, 24, 5),
                (fields.ResourceClass.MEMORY_MB, 32768, 2048),
                (fields.ResourceClass.DISK_GB, 2000, 0),
            ],
            'shared storage': [
                (fields.ResourceClass.DISK_GB, 2000, 50),
            ],
        }
        self._validate_provider_summaries(expected, alloc_cands)

This obviates the need for the _provider_uuids_from_iterable,
_find_summary_for_provider, and _find_summary_for_resource helpers;
those are removed.

Change-Id: Ia719a5697b7d033bcf100c9125b58cd226da7400

"}, {'created': '2017-11-14 17:30:33.000000000', 'message': "Test helper: validate provider summaries

Introduce two helper methods in AllocationCandidatesTestCase.  In a
similar vein to _validate_allocation_requests, they allows the consumer
to specify the expected values in a terse and readable format.

- _validate_provider_summary_resources validates the resources portion
  of the provider_summaries in allocation candidates, e.g.:

        expected = {
            'cn1': set([
                (fields.ResourceClass.VCPU, 24, 5),
                (fields.ResourceClass.MEMORY_MB, 32768, 2048),
                (fields.ResourceClass.DISK_GB, 2000, 0),
            ]),
            'shared storage': set([
                (fields.ResourceClass.DISK_GB, 2000, 50),
            ]),
        }
        self._validate_provider_summary_resources(expected, alloc_cands)

- _validate_provider_summary_traits validates the traits portion of the
  provider_summaries in allocation candidates, e.g.:

        expected = {
            'cn1': set(['HW_CPU_X86_AVX2']),
            'cn2': set(['HW_CPU_X86_AVX2']),
            'shared storage': set(['MISC_SHARES_VIA_AGGREGATE',
                                   'STORAGE_DISK_SSD]),
        }
        self._validate_provider_summary_traits(expected, alloc_cands)

The _provider_uuids_from_iterable, _find_summary_for_provider, and
_find_summary_for_resource helpers are rendered obsolete by the above,
and are therefore removed.

Change-Id: Ia719a5697b7d033bcf100c9125b58cd226da7400

commit_message:
Test helper: validate provider summaries

Introduce two helper methods in AllocationCandidatesTestCase.  In a
similar vein to _validate_allocation_requests, they allows the consumer
to specify the expected values in a terse and readable format.

- _validate_provider_summary_resources validates the resources portion
  of the provider_summaries in allocation candidates, e.g.:

        expected = {
            'cn1': set([
                (fields.ResourceClass.VCPU, 24, 5),
                (fields.ResourceClass.MEMORY_MB, 32768, 2048),
                (fields.ResourceClass.DISK_GB, 2000, 0),
            ]),
            'shared storage': set([
                (fields.ResourceClass.DISK_GB, 2000, 50),
            ]),
        }
        self._validate_provider_summary_resources(expected, alloc_cands)

- _validate_provider_summary_traits validates the traits portion of the
  provider_summaries in allocation candidates, e.g.:

        expected = {
            'cn1': set(['HW_CPU_X86_AVX2']),
            'cn2': set(['HW_CPU_X86_AVX2']),
            'shared storage': set(['MISC_SHARES_VIA_AGGREGATE',
                                   'STORAGE_DISK_SSD]),
        }
        self._validate_provider_summary_traits(expected, alloc_cands)

The _provider_uuids_from_iterable, _find_summary_for_provider, and
_find_summary_for_resource helpers are rendered obsolete by the above,
and are therefore removed.

Change-Id: Ia719a5697b7d033bcf100c9125b58cd226da7400

reproduce the failure given all the other entries in docker-puppet.json.

that new file as $CONFIG.

in docker-puppet.json whose config_volume value matches the user

commit_message:
Enable docker-puppet.py for a single config_volume

If docker-puppet.py fails on any config_volume, it can be difficult to
reproduce the failure given all the other entries in docker-puppet.json.
Often to reproduce a single failure, one has to modify the json file,
and remove all other entries, save the result to a new file, then pass
that new file as $CONFIG.

This commit adds the ability to specify $CONFIG_VOLUME, which will cause
docker-puppet.py to only run the configuration for the specified entry
in docker-puppet.json whose config_volume value matches the user
specified value.

Change-Id: I2889647a27a8b891696a6a3e7f78b59a015c2c79
Closes-Bug: #1737043

commit_message:
console: Send bytes to sockets

Sockets expect byte strings. The default string type in Python 3 is
unicode, meaning calls to socket functions with unencoded strings will
fail. Fix two paths where we were potentially sending unicode, thus
resolving this issue. One of these paths is tested here. The other in
currently unexercised code and will be tested in a future change.

Change-Id: If8fb291ae672a01af4bde96d55b487c450fb2564
Implements: bp websocket-proxy-to-host-security

commit_message:
Remove legacy client factory functions

os-client-config provided helper functions for constructing legacy
python-*client objects, as well as Connection and OpenStackCloud
objects.

openstacksdk isn't in the business of constructing python-*client
objects for people, so let's remove these. We also dont' need helper
functions in the openstack.config space for constructing Connection
since we already have openstack.connect for that (and we'll fold
OpenStackCloud in soon enough)

Change-Id: I09e4fe258ff58a8e8aec5919369ff856a5102b76

commit_message:
Remove contrail from haproxy

This patch removes contrail from haproxy, so that the new tripleo haproxy
dynamic endpoint infrastructure can be used.

Change-Id: I4203055e87f9e319c8a27bcd37b3159c15d6c0a3

commit_message:
Add user_id and project_id to container and capsule info

When use "zun --experimental-api capsule-describe <capsule id>"
or "zun show <container id>", user will get the user_id
and project_id.

Change-Id: I52a0fcdaf34d0f9a51f1a1dcf333bf7522846fbe
Signed-off-by: Kevin Zhao <kevin.zhao@arm.com>

commit_message:
Add group to policy management

The move of policy.json into code means the file may not exist. We've
added support to ensure that the file exists in the openstacklib but we
need to make sure the permissions are right for each service. This adds
the group information to the policies so it works right.

Depends-On: I26e8b1384f4f69712da9d06a4c565dfd1f17c9ed
Change-Id: I4dfcf05aa8418df3ee1a13925f0831dc30921186
Co-Authored-By: Alex Schultz <aschultz@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add a mixed mode parser to string_to_bytes

This proposes a "mixed" parsing type that interprets the IEC-ish "i"
units as power-of-two and the SI-style "non-i" units as power-of-ten.
This is a round-about way of saying it is basically making it the same
as the way GNU parted interprets such strings [1].

While I'd be the first to admit it's a bit ugly, I think it could
serve a role for people who have to interpret such strings for
compatability reasons.  In particuarly within diskimage-builder, we've
accepted these strings for partition creation (being modeled on
parted) and I'd certainly like to not have our own unit parser if we
can help it.

[1] https://www.gnu.org/software/parted/manual/html_node/unit.html

Change-Id: I772bcb6651484d68afabd1965e5db033439c6257

commit_message:
Re-enable octavia functional tests

This patch re-enables the octavia functional tests for openstacksdk.

This patch fixes a bug in the l7rule l7policy URI parameter.

This patch also fixes the test_inventory functional test that fails if
there are multiple networks in the tenant.

Change-Id: Iacdc92ec78a9ca0ad3a82172f426ed91a4b9023d

commit_message:
Move doc requirements to own file

OpenStack-Infra now allows the documentation requirements
to be held in their own file instead of being mixed in with
the other requirements. During the changes to enable this,
our previous method of implementing sphinxmark no longer
works due to the jobs no longer using tox at all for the
tests.

We cannot have sphinxmark in newton's test-requirements.txt
as it is not a library included in the global-requirements
file (it is from ocata onwards), so here we move it to the
docs requirements file.

Change-Id: I802f1f56d1a9ecd41fbc9bcec52f5fd7827e38fb

[{'created': '2018-01-09 14:05:07.000000000', 'message': 'Support protocol numbers in security group API

Somewhere along the way we broke supporting numbers in
the security group API that were not in our known list
of protocols.  In order to fix this properly we must
use the correct arguments when using iptables-save, as
it could use a name instead of a number, or vice-versa.
Determined the list of mappings by doing:

 for num in {0..255}; do iptables -A INPUT -p $num; done
 # iptables-save

Change-Id: I5895250b47ddf664d214cf085be693c3897e0c87
Closes-bug: #1716045
Closes-bug: #1716790
(cherry picked from commit 7ff492c5bb9ce9f24f12db40c8e3a33beb47f87b)
'}]
commit_message:
Support protocol numbers in security group API

Somewhere along the way we broke supporting numbers in
the security group API that were not in our known list
of protocols.  In order to fix this properly we must
use the correct arguments when using iptables-save, as
it could use a name instead of a number, or vice-versa.
Determined the list of mappings by doing:

 for num in {0..255}; do iptables -A INPUT -p $num; done
 # iptables-save

Change-Id: I5895250b47ddf664d214cf085be693c3897e0c87
Closes-bug: #1716045
Closes-bug: #1716790
(cherry picked from commit 7ff492c5bb9ce9f24f12db40c8e3a33beb47f87b)

[{'created': '2018-01-04 15:09:45.000000000', 'message': '[Fullstack] Change how DSCP marking packets are tested

In fullstack test test_dscp_marking_packets two fake hosts are
created, each of them has got one fake instance (called sender and
receiver).
Instance called "sender" sends ICMP packets to instance called
"receiver". In receiver's namespace tcpdump process is spawned with
filter to match only packets marked with specified DSCP value.
After sender instance successfully pings receiver, tcpdump process
is killed and stdout from it was examined to search logged ICMP
packets which were send from sender's IP to receiver's IP address.
That check was failing sometimes as is described in bug report.

It was failing when tcpdump doesn't capture any packets so there was
nothing on stdout from it. But even in such case tcpdump reports on
stderr summary of packets and it was like below:

0 packets captured
6 packets received by filter
0 packets dropped by kernel

which means that packets matching our filter was received by tcpdump but
were probably not processed yet. See [1] for more details.

So this patch changes filter used in tcpdump and way how its output is
checked.
Now in filter expression there are added src and dst IP addresses also so
it will match only packets send from sender instance to receiver instance.
After that tcpdump's stderr output is examined with regex to check if
line like:

X packets received by filter

is there and if X value is different than 0. If so, it means that
tcpdump received packets with wanted DSCP mark and test should pass.

[1] https://unix.stackexchange.com/a/29369

Change-Id: Ia3522237dc787edb90d162ac4a5535ff5d2a03d5
Closes-Bug: #1733649

commit_message:
[Fullstack] Change how DSCP marking packets are tested

In fullstack test test_dscp_marking_packets two fake hosts are
created, each of them has got one fake instance (called sender and
receiver).
Instance called "sender" sends ICMP packets to instance called
"receiver". In receiver's namespace tcpdump process is spawned with
filter to match only packets marked with specified DSCP value.
After sender instance successfully pings receiver, tcpdump process
is killed and stdout from it was examined to search logged ICMP
packets which were send from sender's IP to receiver's IP address.
That check was failing sometimes as is described in bug report.

It was failing when tcpdump doesn't capture any packets so there was
nothing on stdout from it. But even in such case tcpdump reports on
stderr summary of packets and it was like below:

0 packets captured
6 packets received by filter
0 packets dropped by kernel

which means that packets matching our filter was received by tcpdump but
were probably not processed yet. See [1] for more details.

So this patch changes filter used in tcpdump and way how its output is
checked.
Now in filter expression there are added src and dst IP addresses also so
it will match only packets send from sender instance to receiver instance.
After that tcpdump's stderr output is examined with regex to check if
line like:

X packets received by filter

is there and if X value is different than 0. If so, it means that
tcpdump received packets with wanted DSCP mark and test should pass.

[1] https://unix.stackexchange.com/a/29369

Change-Id: Ia3522237dc787edb90d162ac4a5535ff5d2a03d5
Closes-Bug: #1733649

commit_message:
Save updated libvirt domain XML after swapping volume

When a user calls the volume-update API, we swap_volume in the libvirt
driver from the old volume attachment to the new volume attachment.
Currently, we're saving the domain XML with the old configuration prior
to updating the volume and upon a soft-reboot request, it results in an
error:

  Instance soft reboot failed: Cannot access storage file <old path>

and falls back to a hard reboot, which is like pulling the power cord,
possibly resulting in file system inconsistencies.

This changes to saving the new, updated domain XML after the volume
swap.

Closes-Bug: #1713857

NOTE(melwitt): The assert in test_swap_volume_block_old_libvirt had to
be modified to account for the additional XMLDesc call from the bug
fix. The test_swap_volume_block_old_libvirt doesn't exist in Pike, so
that's why we didn't hit this in the master patch.

Change-Id: I166cde5ad8b00699e4ec02609f0d7b69236d855d
(cherry picked from commit 5b008c6540f948d28dc50a0ef84095ebd96d198d)

commit_message:
Qualify the Placement 1.15 release note

When reading the nova release notes together, it might be easy
for someone to not realize this release note is talking about the
Placement API, so this change adds that qualifier to the note.

[{'created': '2017-11-29 15:34:56.000000000', 'message': "Save updated libvirt domain XML after swapping volume

When a user calls the volume-update API, we swap_volume in the libvirt
driver from the old volume attachment to the new volume attachment.
Currently, we're saving the domain XML with the old configuration prior
to updating the volume and upon a soft-reboot request, it results in an
error:

  Instance soft reboot failed: Cannot access storage file <old path>

and falls back to a hard reboot, which is like pulling the power cord,
possibly resulting in file system inconsistencies.

This changes to saving the new, updated domain XML after the volume
swap.

Closes-Bug: #1713857

Change-Id: I166cde5ad8b00699e4ec02609f0d7b69236d855d
(cherry picked from commit 5b008c6540f948d28dc50a0ef84095ebd96d198d)
"}]
commit_message:
Save updated libvirt domain XML after swapping volume

When a user calls the volume-update API, we swap_volume in the libvirt
driver from the old volume attachment to the new volume attachment.
Currently, we're saving the domain XML with the old configuration prior
to updating the volume and upon a soft-reboot request, it results in an
error:

  Instance soft reboot failed: Cannot access storage file <old path>

and falls back to a hard reboot, which is like pulling the power cord,
possibly resulting in file system inconsistencies.

This changes to saving the new, updated domain XML after the volume
swap.

Closes-Bug: #1713857

Change-Id: I166cde5ad8b00699e4ec02609f0d7b69236d855d
(cherry picked from commit 5b008c6540f948d28dc50a0ef84095ebd96d198d)

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-12-21 16:22:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fix an error in _get_host_states when deleting a compute node

_get_host_states returns a generator which closes over seen_nodes, which
is local, and self.host_state_map, which is global. It also modifies
self.host_state_map, and will remove entries whose compute nodes are no
longer present.

If a compute node is deleted while a filter is still evaluating the
generator returned by _get_host_states, the entry in self.host_state_map
will be deleted if _get_host_states is called again. This will cause a
KeyError when the first generator comes to evaluate the entry for the
deleted compute node.

We fix this by modifying the returned generator expression to check
that a host_state_map entry still exists before returning it. An
existing unit test is modified to exhibit the bug.

Conflicts:
      nova/scheduler/filter_scheduler.py
      nova/scheduler/host_manager.py

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict in filter_scheduler.py is due to
48268c73e3f43fa763d071422816942942987f4a in Pike which is not
needed here. The conflict in host_manager.py is due to
d1de5385233ce4379b17a7404557c6724dc37cd4 in Pike which is not
needed here.

Change-Id: Ibb7c43a0abc433f93fc3de71146263e6d5923666
Closes-Bug: #1739323
(cherry picked from commit d72b33b986525a9b2c7aa08b609ae386de1d0e89)
(cherry picked from commit b6a1a192955da3d18f50dfa3130c95fc15d7a66a)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix an error in _get_host_states when deleting a compute node

_get_host_states returns a generator which closes over seen_nodes, which
is local, and self.host_state_map, which is global. It also modifies
self.host_state_map, and will remove entries whose compute nodes are no
longer present.

If a compute node is deleted while a filter is still evaluating the
generator returned by _get_host_states, the entry in self.host_state_map
will be deleted if _get_host_states is called again. This will cause a
KeyError when the first generator comes to evaluate the entry for the
deleted compute node.

We fix this by modifying the returned generator expression to check
that a host_state_map entry still exists before returning it. An
existing unit test is modified to exhibit the bug.

Conflicts:
      nova/scheduler/filter_scheduler.py
      nova/scheduler/host_manager.py

NOTE(mriedem): The conflict in filter_scheduler.py is due to
48268c73e3f43fa763d071422816942942987f4a in Pike which is not
needed here. The conflict in host_manager.py is due to
d1de5385233ce4379b17a7404557c6724dc37cd4 in Pike which is not
needed here.

Change-Id: Ibb7c43a0abc433f93fc3de71146263e6d5923666
Closes-Bug: #1739323
(cherry picked from commit d72b33b986525a9b2c7aa08b609ae386de1d0e89)
(cherry picked from commit b6a1a192955da3d18f50dfa3130c95fc15d7a66a)

commit_message:
Create dedicated "apache" base profile

This profile has multiple purposes:
- group common httpd configurations/instructions
- correct a small issue with the "status" mod

Until now, only Horizon was specifically including this mode, and as
httpd wasn't listening on localhost, it wasn't in use at all.

With this commit, all API using apache will be able to provide the httpd
server status on 127.0.0.1/server-status.

Change-Id: If6d64f807c244d7e56852a67ac7dbad26c4c002f
Closes-Bug: 1724751
(cherry picked from commit 0933bc5fd896ac2474872bb1b4b217ad8f430885)
(cherry picked from commit 8eafd014a8c01826d50c12444271973aace8961b)

commit_message:
Revert "Deduplicate service status notification samples"

This reverts commit 39f9ef719eacb2fbcf0c37680b845152fcff01cc.

The reverted change made the service.update notification sample tests
failing consistently on master. The CI did not catch this problem as
the functional test does not run for changes that only touches
nova/docs. This is a quick fix to unblock the gate and fix the
functional job defintion in a separate patch.

Change-Id: Idabbf70ae46f36be8343c0a00d812cbebf7f7670
Closes-Bug: #1742935

commit_message:
Add group to policy management

The move of policy.json into code means the file may not exist. We've
added support to ensure that the file exists in the openstacklib but we
need to make sure the permissions are right for each service. This adds
the group information to the policies so it works right.

Depends-On: I26e8b1384f4f69712da9d06a4c565dfd1f17c9ed
Change-Id: I2a18f8c3fa4969e083a95bff2b84e01b689b79a4

commit_message:
Disable cephfs_provisioner deployment in openstack namespace

As with the rbd_provisioner deployment, cephfs_provisioner should
only be deployed to the ceph namespace.  This change just disables
that deployment in the openstack namespace.

Change-Id: Idfec8fbdd9408bd292d8770a3690b1b77de2b22d

commit_message:
Edits to Cinder Block Storage Overview

I find the existing wording in this paragraph is too abstract and could
lead the reader to be confused about what is being stated. For example,
"provides an infrastructure for managing volumes" isn't really clear as
"infrastructure" implies HW when the solution is SW. Therefore, the
objective is to provide additional clarity with the least amount of
additional detail. I also made some gramatical changes (commas before
"and" removed) and made the capitalization more consistent.

Best,

Hagen

Change-Id: Ie7475fc04c6213f605319a98690408a40389920e

(2 comments)

Looking at this with the func tests from https://review.openstack.org/#/c/533028/ revealed that we should probably handle non-2xx resource responses. Fixing that caused some *different* tests to fail, where we start sending CORS-enabled responses that were previously blocked, but I think I like the new behavior better? If some JS a CORS request for a DLO with segments it can't list (for example), it seems perfectly reasonable to me that the JS code can see the 401.

The changes to symlink behavior give me a little more pause, but IIRC this better-reflects what we'd discussed when landing the patch."}]

commit_message:
Move CORS to middleware.

This has a couple of benefits. First, it shrinks the proxy a bit and
makes the code cleaner. Now, instead of CORS being something spread
across multiple proxy controllers and kind of hidden away in a
decorator, it's in just one place.

Second, it allows CORS to work with ProxyFS. If you don't run ProxyFS,
and so don't care about that, then just focus on the cleaner-code
aspect. :)

There should be no client-visible changes here.

Change-Id: I88678fddc7a25b0f065b33eb26047321d0db4d38

[{'created': '2018-01-09 16:17:03.000000000', 'message': 'Stable keepalived priorities

The calculation of the keepalived priority depended on the set of hosts
in the ansible_play_hosts variable. This meant that priorites changed
when the playbook was limited to only run on a subset of the hosts in
the "haproxy" group (eg. when reinstalling just one node).

This change replaces ansible_play_hosts by groups["haproxy"] so that the
priority calculation is stable as long as the set of haproxy nodes does
not change. It also simplifies the priority calculation without
changeing the result.

run without --limit and ensures that the configuration does not change
if it is run with --limit.

commit_message:
Stable keepalived priorities

The calculation of the keepalived priority depended on the set of hosts
in the ansible_play_hosts variable. This meant that priorites changed
when the playbook was limited to only run on a subset of the hosts in
the "haproxy" group (eg. when reinstalling just one node).

This change replaces ansible_play_hosts by groups["haproxy"] so that the
priority calculation is stable as long as the set of haproxy nodes does
not change. It also simplifies the priority calculation without
changeing the result.

This change does not change the configuration in case the playbook is
run without --limit and ensures that the configuration does not change
if it is run with --limit.

Change-Id: I378351954fbed7b1fc31303c60e4575ddad9cf1d
(cherry picked from commit 78ed74957dfbd1bb151d0e6b5187fa0c263881ad)

commit_message:
Update all SHAs for Pike 2017-12-20

This patch updates all the roles to the latest available stable
SHA's, copies the release notes from the updated roles into the
integrated repo, updates all the OpenStack Service SHA's, and
updates the appropriate python requirements pins.

Change-Id: I287b8241e3b517303c8fc6086a91ae404e67f46e

commit_message:
Add missing iptable rule in snat ns for centralized fips.

The following iptable rule should be added to snat ns:
"-A neutron-l3-agent-snat -j neutron-l3-agent-float-snat",
or the snat rule will take effect instead of centralized fips
when accessing to the outside for vms.
Closes-Bug: #1735866

Change-Id: I286283bfb4dbf935a34c5919ee0af5225e75fac9

commit_message:
Avoid tox_install.sh for constraints support

We do not need tox_install.sh, pip can handle constraints itself
and install the project correctly. Thus update tox.ini and remove
the now obsolete tools/tox_install.sh file.

This follows https://review.openstack.org/#/c/508061 to remove
tools/tox_install.sh.

Change-Id: I02c57a8eeaf9540e4b94882a581b89533a129350

commit_message:
Update install instructions for memcached

The OBS install instructions for memcached incorrectly instructed the
user to configure memcached to listeon on the localhost address. It
should be configured to use the management IP address of the
controller.

Change-Id: Ia978c025232a80e46cbb12e2ea5fad63c6ad2167
Closes-Bug: #1742884

commit_message:
Add devstack plugin to ease integration tests

Instead of requiring users to install the plugin manually, add a
devstack plugin that can be enabled in order to perform the
installation.

Change the integration tests to use the globally installed plugin
instead of using TEMPEST_PLUGINS.

Change-Id: I3ac8516a0c15b0816c14074ec5119e317735edd6

- gate-tempest-dsvm-heat-identity-v3-only-ubuntu-xenial-nv http://logs.openstack.org/95/459595/1/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-heat-identity-v3-only-ubuntu-xenial-nv/7d55a10/ : SUCCESS in 23m 11s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 8289, 'date': '2017-05-04 10:20:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I prefer the old comparing way:
1. the 'cooldown' is the property of 'group', not for 'one or two' specific actions
2. let's say current time is 7:00 and one scaling is finished,  cooldown is half of an hour, then in 7:10 user find something wrong and hope next scaling after 8:00, in old way, user only has to update the 'cooldown' to an hour, but in the new way, next scaling will be accepted between 7:30~8:00"}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2017-05-05 02:14:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> I prefer the old comparing way:

The cooldown is meant to gives newly-launched instances time to start handling application traffic in an ASG. So what you've mentioned here is a way to maniplulate cooldown for a scaling activity that has happened sometime back. IMO, this is not what it is meant for.

Take the example of multiple policies associated with a group.

	Policy 1: Cooldown 10
	Policy 2: Cooldown 100
	Group: Cooldown 0

If policy 2 based scaling happens immediately followed by one by policy 1, it would not allow for any cooldown from the first scaling (if we add the cooldown period when doing the second scaling, which is 0)

That's also a valid reason to keep the metadata only at one place with group which is in the next patch."}, {'account_id': 8289, 'date': '2017-05-05 02:36:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So, you have to set the 'cooldown' for group if you want to give newly-launched instances time to start handling application traffic in an ASG. 
1. policy or group follows its own 'cooldown' is ok to me
2. also I agree that maybe only group cooldown is enough"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2017-11-14 22:14:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Refactor CooldownMixin

The present way of comparing timestamp in metadata
+ cooldown with current timestamp can be wrong, if
the policy cooldown is updated in between scaling
activity.

Set metadata with the expected cooldown end timestmap
rather than the current timestamp when scaling is finished
and compare it with current timestamp.

Change-Id: I50ddba4c8da3c6ec8b34ebb4768017cb1a446f5f

commit_message:
Latest Nexus Configuration Variables Updates

Add new interface Config variables added to Nexus plugin.
    vnc_pool
    intfcfg_portchannel
    https_verify
    https_local_certificate
Identify variables which are obsolete and those being deprecated.
Change default to switch_heartbeat_time.

Change-Id: I940659bdd448b7bda1c38d9343ec6322390b027a
Closes-bug:  #1672496

commit_message:
Use includes query param to request the SR that includes an object

Instead of passing a/c/o to the container with items=shard to ask
for only the shardrange that holds the object o. Pass it as a param
as this makes the container api cleaner:

  a/c?items=shard&includes=o

Change-Id: I8af213433f2e5cb88f0aac54071a9085a27fc106

[{'account_id': 7634, 'date': '2017-10-20 15:27:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2017-10-20 15:31:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't think we really want to tell people to go directly into the database to remove instance_mappings, they might mess that up.

Coincidentally, tssurya has volunteered to work on removing instance_mappings when running the archive_deleted_rows CLI, which would help with this problem.

Ultimately we really just need to provide a way for operators to clean these things out once the instances are gone, we shouldn't tell them to be doing it manually. Someone might accidentally delete instance mappings for instances that are actually not deleted, by mistake."}, {'account_id': 23498, 'date': '2017-10-20 15:31:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-10-20 15:27:43.000000000', 'message': "Add a warning in 'nova-manage cell_v2 delete_cell'

When deleting a cell, if there are instance mappings to the cell,
the command fails with the following message.

* There are existing instances mapped to cell with uuid UUID.

But even if all instances have been deleted in the cell,
the same message is shown.

So in that case, add a warning that the records should be deleted
in the 'instance_mappings' table before deleting the cell.

Change-Id: I2a163fb50a7e71ce9f463bc9ddeffe2ea47d1588
Closes-Bug: #1725331
"}, {'created': '2017-10-30 10:58:33.000000000', 'message': "Add a warning in 'nova-manage cell_v2 delete_cell'

the command fails with the following message.

* There are existing instances mapped to cell with uuid UUID.

the same message is shown.

So in that case, add a warning that the instance mappings have to
be deleted by 'nova-manage db archive_deleted_rows'
before deleting the cell.

commit_message:
Add a warning in 'nova-manage cell_v2 delete_cell'

When deleting a cell, if there are instance mappings to the cell,
the command fails with the following message.

* There are existing instances mapped to cell with uuid UUID.

But even if all instances have been deleted in the cell,
the same message is shown.

So in that case, add a warning that the instance mappings have to
be deleted by 'nova-manage db archive_deleted_rows'
before deleting the cell.

Change-Id: I2a163fb50a7e71ce9f463bc9ddeffe2ea47d1588
Closes-Bug: #1725331

 -                't' if i < n_desired_queue_updates else 'f')
 +                'f' if i < n_desired_queue_updates else 'f')
 
          for i, node in enumerate(delete_at_nodes or []):
              i = i % len(headers)

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-09 22:23:45.000000000', 'message': 'Limit object-expirer queue updates on object DELETE

Currently, on deletion of an expiring object, each object server
writes an async_pending to update the expirer queue and remove the row
for that object. Each async_pending is processed by the object updater
and results in all container replicas being updated.

If you have Rc container replicas and Ro object replicas (or EC
pieces), then the number of expirer-queue requests made is Rc * Ro [1].

For a 3-replica cluster, that number is 9, which is not terrible. For
a cluster with 3 container replicas and a 15+4 EC scheme, that number
is 57, which is terrible.

This commit makes it so at most two object servers will write out the
async_pending files needed to update the queue, dropping the request
count to 2 * Rc [2]. The object server now looks for a header
"X-Backend-Update-Expiring-Object-Queue: <true|false>" and writes or
does not write expirer-queue async_pendings as appropriate. The proxy
sends that header to 2 object servers.

The queue update is not necessary for the proper functioning of the
object expirer; if the queue update fails, then the object expirer
will try to delete the object, receive 404s, and remove the queue
entry. Removal on object PUT is helpful but not required.

[1] assuming no retries needed by the object updater

[2] or Rc, if a cluster has only one object replica

Change-Id: I4d64f4d1d107c437fd3c23e19160157fdafbcd42
'}, {'created': '2018-01-10 00:34:43.000000000', 'message': 'Limit object-expirer queue updates on object DELETE, PUT, POST

and results in all container replicas being updated. This is also true
for PUT and POST requests for existing expiring objects.

pieces), then the number of expirer-queue requests made is Rc * Ro [1].

For a 3-replica cluster, that number is 9, which is not terrible. For
a cluster with 3 container replicas and a 15+4 EC scheme, that number
is 57, which is terrible.

async_pending files needed to update the queue, dropping the request
count to 2 * Rc [2]. The object server now looks for a header
"X-Backend-Clean-Expiring-Object-Queue: <true|false>" and writes or
does not write expirer-queue async_pendings as appropriate. The proxy
sends that header to 2 object servers.

The queue update is not necessary for the proper functioning of the
object expirer; if the queue update fails, then the object expirer
will try to delete the object, receive 404s or 412s, and remove the
queue entry. Removal on object PUT/POST/DELETE is helpful but not
required.

commit_message:
Limit object-expirer queue updates on object DELETE, PUT, POST

Currently, on deletion of an expiring object, each object server
writes an async_pending to update the expirer queue and remove the row
for that object. Each async_pending is processed by the object updater
and results in all container replicas being updated. This is also true
for PUT and POST requests for existing expiring objects.

If you have Rc container replicas and Ro object replicas (or EC
pieces), then the number of expirer-queue requests made is Rc * Ro [1].

For a 3-replica cluster, that number is 9, which is not terrible. For
a cluster with 3 container replicas and a 15+4 EC scheme, that number
is 57, which is terrible.

This commit makes it so at most two object servers will write out the
async_pending files needed to update the queue, dropping the request
count to 2 * Rc [2]. The object server now looks for a header
"X-Backend-Clean-Expiring-Object-Queue: <true|false>" and writes or
does not write expirer-queue async_pendings as appropriate. The proxy
sends that header to 2 object servers.

The queue update is not necessary for the proper functioning of the
object expirer; if the queue update fails, then the object expirer
will try to delete the object, receive 404s or 412s, and remove the
queue entry. Removal on object PUT/POST/DELETE is helpful but not
required.

[1] assuming no retries needed by the object updater

[2] or Rc, if a cluster has only one object replica

Change-Id: I4d64f4d1d107c437fd3c23e19160157fdafbcd42

commit_message:
Treat device with no MAC address as not ready

There was a recent traceback in the dhcp-agent where
it's tap device did not have a MAC address.  Instead
of failing in init_l3(), have the dhcp-agent fail in
setup() where it verifies the device it is about to
use is ready for use, that way it will release the
port and possibly retry.

Closes-bug: 1742355

Change-Id: Id37396b591946498cdc111eaf4f0c5792e67c53a

commit_message:
Publish neutron and horizon to pypi

The suggestion has been made to publish the server projects to PyPI:

  http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2017-November/124676.html

Doing this will help the neutron and horizon plugin projects not need to
do special things WRT dependencies.

There is an issue to be solved before we can do it for everything.
Keystone is currently https://github.com/dcrosta/keystone on PyPI, not
us. An email has been sent to the maintainer of that package, which
seems very unactive, but no response has happened.

For now, just start publishing neutron and horizon. We already have an
old horizon up there anyway, and we have the neutron entry. If we
approve this, we can also write a one-off script to upload the
older/existing releases from tarballs.o.o.

Change-Id: Ia8cb00045aee3ce8cfc506309ab35477a2d686a1

commit_message:
Adds SSL custom type/provider

New type for configuring SSL in OVS.  Bootstrap mode allows the switch
to accept an initial CA certificate offered by the controller.
Otherwise specify the location of the CA certificate to use in comparing
the controller's cert.  OVS only supports a single instance of SSL
configuration so the provider limits the resource declaration to a
single instance named 'system'.

Partially-Implements: blueprint opendaylight-ssl-support

Change-Id: Ic026ee0bc4f385e0f8cd7076b3044feeb935ae45
Signed-off-by: Tim Rozet <trozet@redhat.com>

commit_message:
tripleo-upgrade: create first tag / branch (independent)

This is a request from the TripleO Upgrades team.
They are working on this new project that run Ansible to control TripleO
upgrades.

They need a stable/pike branch, so this commit is an exceptional request
to create a branch on the latest commit, so the team can go ahead and
push some Queens only commits in master once the branch is created.

It also creates a 1.0.0 for Pike and later we'll create 2.0.0 for
Queens.

Note, this is an independent deliverable this time, because we missed
the Pike deadline.

Change-Id: I111b745fe44a899c24f8e088e4dbf46358ecfa56

[{'account_id': 2, 'date': '2018-01-02 16:34:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8257, 'date': '2018-01-02 20:13:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Does this currently work for everything? Last I worked on this we were solving several pagination behaviors at once. That extra call wasn't always needed, but in some cases (which I can't remember off the top of my head) we needed it, so it was just in there at all times in the interest of always returning the proper amount at the expense of sometimes making one extra call."}, {'account_id': 2, 'date': '2018-01-02 23:24:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

I know it works for nova and cinder - but that's a great question and we should answer it for sure before landing this (marking WIP for that reason) I started in on this when migrating the shade code to use the SDK API and hitting places where the results were additional calls in places that would be very chatty once we make it all the way through the stack and down to nodepool.

I'll take a pass at proving whether it works or not. If it only works on some and not others, maybe we can add a flag to Resource to do pagination using _links or via calculated marker links. At the very least we should wind up with some notes about which services provide _links and which don't."}, {'account_id': 8246, 'date': '2018-01-04 05:33:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:
